<reply id="uk.org.publicwhip/wrans/2005-11-01b.13.8" speakerid="uk.org.publicwhip/lord/100574" speakername="Baroness Scotland of Asthal" colon=":" colnum="13"  url="http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld199900/ldhansrd/pdvn/lds05/text/51101w02.htm#51101w02_spnew1">
	<p pid="b.13.8/1">The Government do not have precise estimates of the cost of providing public services specifically to migrants. In 2002 the Home Office published research into the net fiscal contribution of migrants. This was based on figures for 1999&ndash;2000 and estimated that migrants (defined as foreign born) made a net fiscal contribution of &pound;2.5 billion. This research was recently updated by IPPR based on figures for 2003&ndash;04 (Sriskandarajah, Cooley and Reed: <i>Paying their way: the fiscal contribution of immigrants in the UK</i>, IPPR, London, 2005). This found that migrants (defined as the foreign born) accounted for 9.6 per cent. of the population, yet 1 per cent. of government revenue and only 9.1 percent of government expenditure. The Government do not calculate the capital cost of providing infrastructure as a means of determining the number of immigrants who should be admitted to the UK.</p>
</reply>
